<h2>What is InboxDollars?</h2>
<p>InboxDollars is one of the oldest rewards platforms out there, operating since 2006. They've paid out over $80 million to members. The platform pays you for reading emails, taking surveys, playing games, watching videos, and shopping online.</p>
<p>The big draw is the $5 signup bonus — you get it just for creating an account and confirming your email. No purchase required.</p>

<h2>How Does It Work?</h2>
<p>InboxDollars shows you your balance in actual dollars (not points), which makes it easy to track earnings. You earn by:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Surveys</strong> — typically $0.50-$3.00 each, takes 5-20 minutes</li>
  <li><strong>Games</strong> — play GSN games, scratch cards, and other casual games</li>
  <li><strong>Videos</strong> — watch short video playlists for a few cents each</li>
  <li><strong>Shopping</strong> — cashback on online purchases</li>
  <li><strong>Reading Emails</strong> — $0.02-$0.05 per email (small but passive)</li>
</ul>

<h2>Gaming on InboxDollars</h2>
<p>The gaming section is decent but not as robust as FreeCash. You'll find:</p>
<ul>
  <li>GSN Casino games (slots, poker, solitaire)</li>
  <li>Scratch & Win cards (small cash prizes)</li>
  <li>Occasional game download offers</li>
</ul>
<p>The gaming here is more casual — think solitaire and word games rather than RPGs and strategy titles. If you're a hardcore gamer, FreeCash will have more relevant offers. If you enjoy casual games, InboxDollars is solid.</p>

<h2>The $15 Minimum Cashout Issue</h2>
<p>The biggest downside is the $15 minimum withdrawal. With your $5 signup bonus, you still need to earn $10 more before you can cash out. Depending on how active you are, that could take a few days to a few weeks.</p>
<p>Compare that to FreeCash's $1 minimum and you see the difference. InboxDollars asks for more commitment before you see real money.</p>

<h2>Is InboxDollars Worth It?</h2>
<p>InboxDollars is a solid secondary platform. Grab the $5 bonus, use it alongside FreeCash, and treat it as extra income rather than your primary earning source. The lower per-task rates mean it's best for multitasking — watching videos while doing other things, for example.</p>

<h2>Our Verdict</h2>
<p>InboxDollars is legitimate and has been around for 20 years, which says something. It's not the highest earner, but the free $5 makes it worth trying. Best used alongside a higher-paying platform like FreeCash.</p>

